Mrs. Liu: Yajing, I've been thinking about getting a new stand mixer recently. Which one has caught your eye?
Song Yajing: Lily, I'm still doing my homework. There are too many choices on the market, and it's overwhelming.
Mrs. Liu: Yes, some brands are just good-looking, while others are particularly cheap. What aspects do you mainly focus on?

Song Yajing: My current thinking is that appearance and brand are secondary; a moderate price is fine. What I value most is the material itself—it must be durable and, most importantly, made of food-contact-grade safe material. After all, it's for preparing food, so safety comes first, and it gives me peace of mind to use it.
Mrs. Liu: That's right! I think so too. Durability and safety are the most important. Otherwise, if it breaks down soon or poses health risks, it would be really troublesome.
Li Meiling: Jingjing, have you heard? It seems something good is happening with Jiajia.
Song Yajing: Huh? I was just busy in the shop and didn't check my phone. What's wrong with Jiajia? Tell me quickly!

Li Meiling: She posted a message in our group of three last night. Didn’t you see it? She said the new product her team had been working on for over half a year was officially launched last week, and the response has been fantastic.

Mrs. Liu: Please share your shopping tips! The one in my home has been used for several years, and I'm thinking about replacing it.

Song Yajing: I spent a long time choosing this time. I didn't pursue an exceptionally large capacity; as long as it's sufficient for home use, that's fine. I don't think those fancy smart features are particularly useful. What I value most is temperature control!

Song Yajing: Especially when making macarons and chiffon cakes, a few degrees difference in temperature can greatly affect the outcome. That's why I specifically chose an oven with electronic temperature control. It is said to maintain a temperature variance within plus or minus 5 degrees, which gives me much more confidence when baking.

message_content: Aunt Zhang, during our chat with Xiao Wang in the garden this afternoon, we had an in-depth discussion about the idea of quarterly activities. He emphasized the importance of a written proposal, and I will organize the draft as soon as possible and send it to him for reference. We'll schedule another time next week to refine the plan.
Aunt Zhang: Teacher Song, today's class was so practical! I especially loved the method of turning old shirts into shopping bags. I'll try making a few when I get home.
Li Meiling: Jingjing, have you been in touch with Jiajia recently? I feel like her social media posts seem a bit down.
Song Yajing: Well, we had a video call last week. She's been having some trouble at work recently, which is quite upsetting.
Li Meiling: What's wrong? Is it still the pressure from that project?
Song Yajing: It's not about the project. She said her company recently underwent a structural reorganization, and the entire product line she was responsible for was merged into another department.

Song Yajing: Now she has to reapply for her position. Although the company says there will be no layoffs, the competition is fierce. She is under immense pressure, worried about not finding a suitable spot.
Master Chen: Xiao Song, have you tried any new desserts recently?
Song Yajing: Hello, Teacher Chen! I've been challenging myself with mousse cakes lately and want to make them more refined.
Song Yajing: But I always run into problems when making the glaze. The prepared mirror glaze cracks and becomes uneven after cooling, and I've tried several times with the same result.

Chef Chen: The glazing of a mousse cake indeed requires some skill. Cracking is usually due to poor temperature control or the mousse not being frozen hard enough. How long did you freeze the mousse? What was the temperature of the glaze?

Song Yajing: I froze the mousse for over 4 hours, so it should be firm enough. I cooled the glaze to around 35 degrees Celsius before pouring it, as per the tutorial. Could the issue be with the proportion of gelatin or the cooking time?
Li Meiling: Jingjing, I just finished a video call with Jiajia. She hasn't been doing well lately.
Song Yajing: Huh? What's wrong? Too busy with work?
Li Meiling: Yes, her company recently underwent a major organizational restructuring, and the impact was particularly significant.

Li Meiling: She said their entire product line has been merged, and now everyone has to reapply for their positions, which has caused a lot of anxiety. She’s under immense pressure and mentioned that she hasn’t been sleeping well lately.
Song Yajing: Oh my god, this is so sudden. No wonder she's been talking less in the group chat lately. We need to find time to comfort her more.
Mrs. Liu: Jingjing, I saw the photos of the tiramisu you made last time. The cocoa powder was sprinkled so evenly, and the color looks great! What brand did you use?
Song Yajing: Thanks, Lily! I've been doing some research on cocoa powder lately. I used to use it casually, but now I realize there's a huge difference.

Song Yajing: I now consistently use a Dutch imported unsweetened cocoa powder. Although it's a bit more expensive, the color is a very authentic deep brown, and the aroma is particularly rich and pure, without any sour or burnt bitterness. Sprinkling it instantly elevates the quality.
Mrs. Liu: Made in the Netherlands? That sounds professional! Send me the link, I'd like to try it too. Are you still using that common brand for mascarpone?

Song Yajing: Yes, Mascarpone is still the one to use, it's stable. But regarding the cocoa powder, I think I've found the right one—the Dutch process really makes a difference. I'll send you the link via WeChat.
Li Meiling: Jingjing, are you busy? I just finished a video call with Jiajia, and it feels like she's under a lot of work pressure lately.
Song Yajing: Just got home after closing the shop. What's wrong with Jiajia? Isn't she always very resilient?

Li Meiling: Yes, but this time it seems a bit tricky. She said she's recently been in charge of a rather important product project, and the team has hired a new UI designer who is particularly stubborn in their ideas.
Song Yajing: Oh? Is there a conflict in product direction?

Li Meiling: It's not about the overall direction, but mainly the interface style. Jiajia wants a simple and modern style, but the designer insists on adding some retro elements. Neither of them can convince the other, and they've argued several times in meetings. Jiajia says it's particularly difficult to communicate, and the project progress has been delayed. She's quite anxious, worried it might affect the launch timeline.
Mrs. Liu: Yajing, I recently tried making a passion fruit-flavored tiramisu. I'll send you a picture to see! It feels quite refreshing.
Song Yajing: Wow, it looks amazing! But to be honest, Lily, among all the flavors of tiramisu, the passion fruit one is the hardest for me to accept.
Mrs. Liu: Huh? Why is that? I think the sourness helps cut through the greasiness.

Song Yajing: I tried it once. The sourness of the passion fruit is too "overpowering." As soon as you take a bite, its flavor dominates, completely masking the aroma of the coffee liqueur and cocoa powder. The layered progression of coffee, liqueur, and cheese that defines tiramisu is completely lost. I don’t think it qualifies as tiramisu anymore.
Song Yajing: In comparison, the matcha flavor is a bit bitter, but still harmonious. Strawberry is acceptable if handled properly. But as for passion fruit, I won't be making it again.
Li Meiling: Jingjing, are you busy? I just finished a video call with Jiajia, and she has some good news!
Song Yajing: Lingling! I just closed the shop, not busy. What good news? Tell me quickly!
Li Meiling: Jiajia's company has been conducting internal competitions for quite some time, and it's been going on for nearly half a year. The results finally came out today!
Song Yajing: Wow! She mentioned it before, the pressure was immense. How did it turn out?

Li Meiling: She made it! She got promoted from Product Manager to Senior Product Manager! Although she's still at the same company in Shenzhen, both her rank and salary have increased. She said she’ll treat us to a meal when she returns to Fujian next time.
Mrs. Liu: Yajing, you mentioned wanting to buy a coffee machine last time. Have you looked into it? My friend recommended De'Longhi, saying it's quite good.
Song Yajing: Lily, I've looked at several models and my head is spinning. There are just too many brands.
Mrs. Liu: Haha, I understand. What do you mainly want to use it for? Making milk foam for lattes?

Song Yajing: That's not necessarily required. Actually, my needs are quite simple. Mornings are tight—I have to drop off Xuanxuan and open the shop. I just want something that's the easiest to operate, ideally with a single button to brew an Americano or an espresso. I don’t want anything too complicated. Fancy features are unnecessary for me.

Mrs. Liu: I see, you're a practical person who values minimalism and efficiency. You might want to consider some entry-level models that focus on "one-touch" operation. They offer good value for money and align with your core need for convenience and speed.

Xiaomei: Good morning, Sister Yajing. As discussed in the morning meeting, I'll start by organizing the inventory and picking out the summer items suitable for display. Please let me know if you need any help with adjusting the window display.

Zhiqiang, regarding the alternative plans for our parents' relocation that we discussed yesterday, I've drafted a few ideas. For example, if the community inspection doesn't go well, we could consider renting an apartment nearby. Shall we discuss it over the phone tonight?
Me: The museum is really nice. Lexuan had a great time and kept circling around that self-playing antique piano, saying it was amazing. Have you arrived home?

Yajing, the fund names and monthly fixed deposit amounts from the meeting resolution have been finalized: 2000 yuan for the Daughter's Education Fund and 1000 yuan for the Family Travel Fund. Automatic transfers have been set up.
Li Meiling: Jingjing, have you been in touch with Fangfang recently? She seems to be in a particularly bad mood lately.
Song Yajing: We had a video call last week, and I felt she wasn't in high spirits. But she said she was busy with work, so I didn't ask further. What's wrong?
Li Meiling: Sigh, there have been major changes at her company. Their entire product line has been cut, and the whole team is being disbanded.
Song Yajing: Huh? So sudden! What about Fangfang then?

Li Meiling: The company gave a grace period, but it's only one month. If she can't find an internal transfer or a new job within a month, she'll have to leave Shenzhen and return to Quanzhou. She said she's been sending out resumes and going to interviews every day, and the stress is so overwhelming that she can't sleep and is losing a lot of hair. It seems she's really anxious, afraid that all these years in Shenzhen will have been for nothing.
Mrs. Liu (Lily): Jingjing, have you been researching any new desserts lately? I made a Mont Blanc with chestnuts, but I think I added too much sugar—it's a bit too rich.
Song Yajing: Haha, chestnuts themselves are quite sweet, so less sugar is needed. Recently, I've been working on a "Earl Grey Tea Mille Crêpe Cake."
Mrs. Liu (Lily): Wow! It sounds very stylish just from the name. Is it French? What filling are you planning to use? Traditional custard or diplomat cream?

Song Yajing: It's more of an improvement. I don't really like the overly heavy texture of traditional mille-feuille fillings. I tried several variations and finally found that using light cream infused with Earl Grey tea leaves for the filling layer creates the most unique flavor.

Song Yajing: The tea fragrance can balance the sweetness of the cream, making the texture lighter. Paired with the mille-feuille pastry, it feels more layered and interesting. I think it’s more appealing than using pure custard or diplomat cream.
Li Meiling: Jingjing, have you been in touch with Jiajia recently? I feel like she's not quite herself.
Song Yajing: I just had a video call with her last night. She's been under a lot of work pressure lately and seems completely drained.
Li Meiling: Is it still because of the launch of that new product? I remember she mentioned it before and put a lot of effort into it.

Song Yajing: Yes, that's the one. She said that after the launch, user feedback was mediocre, with even some negative reviews, and the team's morale was low. As the product manager, she felt immense pressure.

Song Yajing: When she talked to me, she even mentioned that she was considering leaving her current company and trying a new environment. I advised her not to act impulsively and to take some time to calm down.
Mrs. Liu: Yajing, the chiffon cake you posted on your Moments looks so delicate and fine! Did you make it with the new oven?
Song Yajing: Yes, Lily! I just changed it. The old oven had inaccurate temperature control, so baking always ended in disaster. This time, I made up my mind to replace it.
Mrs. Liu: Which brand did you choose? Nowadays, ovens have so many functions, it must be overwhelming to pick one, right?

Song Yajing: The brand isn't what I value most. This time, my core requirements are just two things: first, the temperature control must be precise—this is fundamental, otherwise baking would be a disaster. Second, it's best if it has a steam function, as I want to try baking some European-style bread and baguettes.
Mrs. Liu: That makes sense! Temperature control is the soul. The crusty bread baked in an oven with steam is indeed different. The model you chose seems very professional.

Zhiqiang: Yajing, I've put the box of books and photo albums from Xiamen in the car, arranged for the recycling of the old appliances, and the pile of trash to be discarded will be collected by the property management tomorrow.
Yuexuan: Mom, do the fabric scraps on the inspiration board look good? We can use more fashion magazine cutouts next time.
Li Meiling: Jingjing, have you heard? Jiajia had an accident in Shenzhen.
Song Yajing: Huh? What happened? Is it serious?

Li Meiling: She has been working overtime to meet project deadlines recently, pulling several all-nighters in a row. As a result, she developed acute gastroenteritis and was in so much pain that her colleagues took her straight to the emergency room.
Song Yajing: Oh my god, that's too much. How is the person doing now?

Li Meiling: I'm feeling much better after the IV drip. The doctor suggested staying in the hospital for observation for a day. She told me not to tell you, afraid you'd worry. Sigh, we're far apart and can't really help much, so we can only call more often to show our concern.
Mrs. Liu: Yajing, what brand of chocolate did you use for the Black Forest cake you made last time? The shine and texture were both excellent.
Song Yajing: I use Valrhona 66%. When I choose chocolate now, I don't pay much attention to whether the brand is the most famous; I mainly focus on two points.
Mrs. Liu: Which two points? Please tell me quickly, I want to learn as well.

Song Yajing: First, the cocoa butter content must be high, as this ensures a fine texture after melting, making it ideal for creating ganache or glazes. Second, the mouthfeel must be smooth, without any graininess or strange sour or astringent flavors, as these can affect the overall flavor profile of the dessert. Price isn’t my top priority, since the quantity used isn’t large—quality is more important.
Mrs. Liu: That makes sense! It seems I should also upgrade my ingredient inventory. Thanks for sharing!
Li Meiling: Yajing, have you been busy lately? It's been a while since we last got together.
Song Yajing: Yes, Lingling. My parents just moved in recently, and the shop is busy with seasonal updates, so I’ve been a bit overwhelmed. How about you?
Li Meiling: I'm doing okay, just busy with the graduating class. By the way, have you been in touch with Jiajia recently? It seems like she's up to something big.
Song Yajing: I did! She had a video call with me last week and said that her company held an internal competition for promotion, and she successfully advanced. She is now the Product Director.
Li Meiling: Wow! That's amazing! But with the promotion, are you busier now?

Song Yajing: Exactly. She said she's under immense pressure now, with meetings running late every day. But this is her career pursuit, and I'm genuinely happy for her. It's just that we're far apart, so I can't really help much.
Mrs. Liu: Yajing, could you send me the recipe for that matcha mille crepe cake you made last time? The layers in mine never seem distinct enough.

Song Yajing: Lily, I'll send you the recipe via WeChat. I've been so busy lately that I haven't had time to work on new pastries. Our old car at home has been having some issues, and I'm thinking about replacing it. I've looked at several models, and it's making my head spin.
Mrs. Liu: Buying a new car is a big decision! Do you have any models in mind? There are many new energy vehicle options available now.

Song Yajing: Aqiang and I have discussed it, and our main consideration is practicality for family use. Brand and appearance are actually not that important; what we value most is space, especially the back seat being spacious and comfortable.

Song Yajing: After all, my parents have moved to Xiamen now, and we often go out as a family on weekends. The back seat is for my parents and Xuanxuan, so it definitely can’t be cramped. Fuel consumption and maintenance are also important, of course, but comfort and spaciousness come first.
Mrs. Liu: I understand, practicality is indeed the most important factor for a family car. When we were choosing a car, we also prioritized backseat space and seat comfort first.
Li Meiling: Jingjing, have you been in touch with Jiajia recently? It seems like she's gone off the grid again.

Song Yajing: Yes, I've been in touch with her. We even had a video call last week. She mentioned that her company recently organized some kind of product innovation camp. It's a closed-door event, lasting for a week, and it seems to be held at a resort somewhere in Huizhou. They have pretty strict rules about phone usage there.
Li Meiling: Oh, I see. Her work schedule is even busier than ours running a shop. A week of isolation—what about her husband and children?

Song Yajing: Her mother-in-law is going to help take care of the child for a few days. Well, that's how it is in their internet company—they often have closed-door development sessions or innovation camps. But she seems to enjoy it quite a bit, saying she gets to explore many new ideas. Anyway, it doesn’t affect us. We can catch up when she’s back.
Li Meiling: That's true. So, are we still having our baking gathering this weekend? I've just learned a new recipe for red velvet cake.
Mrs. Liu: Yajing, have you found any good red wines lately? My husband's company gave out two bottles at their annual party, but they tasted quite astringent.

Song Yajing: Haha, the one we usually drink at home is pretty good. Neither Aqiang nor I like wines that are too sour or astringent. We specifically choose ones with a strong fruity aroma, like cherry or blackberry scents—they smell so pleasant.
Mrs. Liu: Exactly, exactly. The ones with a good fruity aroma bring a strong sense of pleasure when drinking. Are they expensive?

Song Yajing: Not expensive at all, it's just for daily meals, around one to two hundred yuan. I think when it comes to drinking, it's not about collecting; what matters most is that it tastes good and is affordable. We don't really understand those famous estate wines, so the ones with high cost-effectiveness are the most suitable for our family.
Mrs. Liu: That makes sense! Send me the brand, and I'll give it a try too. Next time, try pairing it with the cookies I sent you—it’s absolutely amazing.
Mrs. Liu: Yajing, Happy New Year! Have you been busy lately? I've been feeling a bit bored recently; my husband has gone to Shenzhen again.
Song Yajing: Happy New Year, Lily! Yes, the shop has been a bit busy just after the New Year. Why did your husband go to Shenzhen again? Didn't he just come back?

Mrs. Liu: Don't even mention it. Their company has taken on a new project and needs to collaborate closely with the team in Shenzhen, requiring core members from both sides to hold regular face-to-face meetings. This is already his third time flying there this month, and he'll probably have to go again next month.
Song Yajing: That's quite frequent, it must be really tiring. Being home alone is a great opportunity to experiment with new desserts, haha.
Song Yawen: Jingjing, are you busy? I want to talk to you. I've been thinking about changing my car recently.
Song Yajing: Just finished putting Xuanxuan to sleep. Thinking of changing cars? Which model have you got your eye on?

Song Yawen: I've looked at several models and test-driven the BBA ones. The BMW 3 Series handles well, but I think the interior is just average. The Audi A4L has a strong sense of technology, but its appearance is a bit too rigid.

Song Yawen: In the end, I still feel that the interior of the Mercedes-Benz C-Class suits my taste the most. The ambient lighting and the dual-screen setup create a completely different atmosphere once you sit inside. Although many say it doesn’t offer the best value for money, I just love that vibe.
Song Yajing: Haha, sis, you're still so focused on the feeling. If you like it, just buy it. What matters most is that you enjoy driving it yourself.

Xiaomei: Yajing, several customers who just checked out used the online coupons you issued and redeemed them directly. There are also two orders for in-store pickup that have arrived; I've already found the items and placed them at the front desk.

message_content: Xiaomei, I have just refined the time frame of the sharing topic to 'My Ten-Year Fashion Journey.' Combined with the previous core idea, the complete theme should encompass the entire journey.
Aunt Zhang: Jingjing, I really enjoyed our chat this morning. I'll follow up with the neighborhood committee about the old clothes upcycling workshop.
Mrs. Liu: Yajing, how have you been lately? I've been a bit troubled recently and wanted to talk to someone.
Song Yajing: Lily, what's wrong? You sound a bit down. I just finished up at the shop, tell me.
Mrs. Liu: Sigh, it's about my husband's work. He's been under a lot of pressure lately and often works overtime until midnight.
Song Yajing: Is the project not going smoothly? I remember he seems to be in charge of a fairly large project.

Mrs. Liu: Yes, it's a smart city project for the Hangzhou government, which was supposed to be his most important achievement this year. However, the client recently tightened their budget, and the project funding was slashed by more than half. Now the whole project is stuck, and it might even fall through. Everyone on his team is feeling anxious.

Chen Zhiqiang: Honey, today when I picked up Xuanxuan from school, I heard from her classmate's mom that they are enrolling their child in an Olympiad math class, saying it will be useful for future school admissions. Should we also look into it?
Song Yajing: Aqiang, I firmly disagree with this. Starting Olympiad math in elementary school only leads to endless practice and pressure, which completely kills a child's interest.
Chen Zhiqiang: What about English? Nowadays, many children are taking classes with foreign teachers to practice their spoken English.

Song Yajing: It's fine to expose children to English appropriately, mainly for fun, and I don't oppose that. Activities like learning musical instruments or painting, which cultivate aesthetic appreciation and patience, also seem quite good to me. However, when it comes to Olympiad math classes, I really don't want Xuanxuan to suffer through that at such a young age. It completely goes against the original intention of happy growth.
Li Meiling: Jingjing, are you busy? I just finished a video call with Jiajia, and she shared some juicy gossip with me!
Song Yajing: Just finished putting Xuanxuan to sleep. What's the gossip? Tell me, tell me!
Li Meiling: Jiajia was urged by her mother to go on a blind date last month, and she actually met a guy who works at an investment bank in Shenzhen, seems to be doing financial analysis.
Song Yajing: Wow! A finance guy? Is he reliable? How does Jiajia feel about him?

Li Meiling: She said she feels okay about him, and he's quite a gentleman, but he's particularly busy with work. They just occasionally go out for meals and watch movies—it's more like they're just starting to get to know each other. Sigh, among the three of us, she's the only one still single. I hope things go smoothly for her this time. But her situation is far from us and doesn't really affect us much—I'm just happy for her.
Chef Chen: Yajing, did you try making the red velvet cake we taught in the last class at home?

Song Yajing: Hello, Teacher Chen! I tried it, and it was very successful! However, I’ve recently been experimenting on my own and have become fascinated with making pound cakes. I feel they have a richer texture compared to chiffon cakes.
Chef Chen: Oh? Pound cake is indeed great for playing with flavors. What have you been adding to it lately?

Song Yajing: My favorite combination is "Earl Grey Lemon"! I grind the Earl Grey tea leaves and add them to the batter, and the baked goods come out with an incredibly rich tea aroma. Paired with a touch of fresh, tangy lemon zest, it perfectly balances the richness of the butter. My husband and kids say it tastes even better than the ones you can buy outside.

Master Chen: This combination is classic, showing that your taste has improved. The tea aroma and fruity acidity indeed enhance the layers of the pound cake. Next time, you can try brushing a layer of lemon syrup on the surface.
Jingjing, your cousin Xiaofang works in insurance. I've shared her WeChat contact with you. You two should schedule a time to discuss retirement planning.
Jian Guo, I've given it some thought. How about you start getting involved with the online customer service and order processing for the shop tomorrow? I'll guide you through it.
Li Meiling: Jingjing, have you heard? There's news from Jiajia!
Song Yajing: What news? I just finished taking inventory at the shop, tell me quickly!
Li Meiling: She had been preparing for that internal promotion, and the results came out today—she succeeded!
Song Yajing: Wow! That's great! Is it a promotion? What's the specific position?

Li Meiling: Yes, she got promoted to Senior Product Manager! She said her total compensation package increased by about 30%, and the pressure is greater too, but she’s quite confident. She just sent a red envelope in our group chat of three, hurry up and grab it!
Mrs. Liu: Jingjing, the chiffon cake you posted on your Moments looks so delicate! Did you make it with your new oven?
Song Yajing: Yes, Lily! The temperature control on my old oven wasn't very accurate, so I just replaced it last month. It took me a long time to choose.
Mrs. Liu: Please share your experience. Mine has also been used for several years, and I'm considering replacing it. What aspects do you value the most?

Song Yajing: First and foremost, temperature control must be accurate. Even a few degrees off can make a big difference when making desserts. Second is capacity. I often bake two trays of cookies or an eight-inch cake along with several cupcakes at once, so insufficient space just won't do.

Song Yajing: The third point is ease of cleaning! The inner pot should ideally be enamel-coated, so grease can be wiped off effortlessly. As for those flashy smart features, I don’t think they’re necessary—solid basic functionality is what matters most.
Li Meiling: Jingjing, are you busy? I have something to tell you about Jiajia.
Song Yajing: Just finished tidying up the shop, not busy. What's up with Jiajia?

Li Meiling: She's been on a blind date in Shenzhen recently, arranged by her family. Yesterday, she told me via video call that she met a man who has a good job and family background, working as a manager in a tech company.
Li Meiling: But he's just too dull, hardly says a word during meals or movies. Jiajia says it feels like dating a block of wood. She's really torn now, unsure whether to keep seeing him.
Song Yajing: Oh, I see. Jiajia has such a lively personality, so she might not get along with someone too reserved. I'll talk to her later and see what she thinks.
Mrs. Liu: Jingjing, have you made any new desserts recently? I tried making matcha mille crepe, but I think I added too much sugar—it feels a bit too rich.
Song Yajing: Lily, I've recently become obsessed with making all kinds of fruit tarts. There are so many fruits in summer. I've discovered a trick!

Song Yajing: In the past, when I made custard sauce, I was always afraid it wouldn't be sweet enough, so I would add plenty of sugar. Now I think it tastes better with a little less sugar, about 1/4 to 1/3 less than the standard recipe.

Song Yajing: This way, the buttery aroma of the tart base and the sweet and sour taste of the fruit itself are more prominent, making the overall flavor fresher and less sweet and greasy. Both my daughter Xuanxuan and my husband said it tastes better this way.
Mrs. Liu: This adjustment idea is great! Healthy and delicious. Next time I make fruit tarts, I'll also try reducing the sugar. Thanks for sharing!
Li Meiling: Jingjing, have you heard? Jiajia has the latest news!
Song Yajing: Huh? What news? She hasn't been talking much in our group chat lately.

Li Meiling: She privately messaged me late last night, saying she has been quietly interviewing for the past few months. A headhunter approached her and recommended a position as a senior product manager at a major internet company in Shenzhen, with a salary significantly higher than her current one!
Song Yajing: Wow! Really? Is that company much larger than her current one? Has she decided to go?

Li Meiling: Well, the company is much larger, and the platform is better. She said she has accepted the offer and will start next month. However, she asked me not to mention it in the group chat for now and to wait until things are stable before making an official announcement. She’s been busy with the handover recently and is under a lot of pressure. Sigh, we’re still following the routine here in Xiamen, while her career has taken another step forward.

Song Yajing: I'm really happy for her! Although she's further away from us now, it's a good thing that she's doing well. My little shop is a completely different world from her big company job-hopping, so it doesn't affect me here. When she comes back for the Spring Festival, we'll have to treat ourselves to a big celebration meal at her expense!
Mrs. Liu: Yajing, I recently discovered a local coffee roaster in Hangzhou, and their beans are excellent. Do you usually drink coffee at home? What flavors do you prefer?
Song Yajing: Yes, but not that professionally. A-Qiang enjoys pour-over coffee, so I just follow along. We’ve been picking out our daily coffee beans recently and have tried quite a few.
Mrs. Liu: Any preferences? I like ones with a pronounced fruity acidity, like Yirgacheffe.

Song Yajing: I'm a bit different from you. I've tried a few coffees that were too acidic, and they felt a bit harsh, not really my thing. When I choose beans now, the acidity has to be mild, not too sharp, so it's comfortable to drink.
Mrs. Liu: I see, so you prefer a full-bodied type?

Song Yajing: Yes, and in terms of flavor, I particularly enjoy those with nutty or chocolate notes, such as beans from Colombia or Brazil. They feel especially aromatic, and having a cup in the morning is very satisfying. The price should be moderate—no need to go for the top-tier, but I also don’t want cheap commercial beans that only taste bitter.
Mrs. Liu: Such specific preferences! A smooth acidity with nutty chocolate notes. I've noted it down and will recommend suitable beans to you next time.
Li Meiling: Jingjing, have you heard? There's news from Jiajia!
Song Yajing: Huh? What news? Isn't she busy with a big project recently?
Li Meiling: The project was a success! She just said in the group chat that the company officially appointed her as the Product Director! I'm so happy for her!
Song Yajing: Wow! Really? That's fantastic! Jiajia has always been so hardworking; she truly deserves this. We must congratulate her properly!

Li Meiling: Indeed, but her promotion and salary increase are all in Shenzhen, so it doesn’t directly affect our lives in Xiamen. I’m just happy for her—it feels like we have another strong female role model in our childhood friend circle!
Mrs. Liu: Yajing, have you tried any new recipes lately? There are so many fruits in spring. I made a mango mousse, and it turned out quite nice.

Song Yajing: Lily, I was just about to tell you! I’ve recently gotten into making all kinds of fruit tarts. Strawberry season is here, and the strawberry tarts I made were a hit with my family—they said they taste even better than plain cakes and really capture the feeling of spring.
Mrs. Liu: Fruit tarts are indeed perfect for this season! The crust is key—what recipe do you use?

Song Yajing: I referred to the recipe for sablé tart crust given by Teacher Chen, which is quite flaky. I plan to focus on researching various seasonal fruit tarts over the next few months, such as blueberry, peach, and fig tarts. I feel this direction is not only seasonal but also visually appealing for plating.

Mrs. Liu: This plan sounds great! It's seasonal and healthy. Once you've perfected your signature recipe, I must try it when I return to Xiamen! Macarons and fondant are too sweet and complicated; fruit tarts are much more down-to-earth.
Susan: Song Yajing, the schedule adjustment for the autumn ordering meeting has been initially communicated. Please confirm the new arrangement month as soon as possible.
Li Meiling: Jingjing, have you been in touch with Jiajia recently? I feel like she's been a bit down.
Song Yajing: We had a video chat last week. She seemed quite unhappy with her job, saying she felt like she had hit a dead end.

Li Meiling: Yes, that's exactly what she told me too. She said that after working for several years at that big company in Shenzhen, there are very few promotion opportunities now. Every day, the projects she works on are pretty much the same, with nothing new to learn, and she finds it quite boring.
Song Yajing: Hmm, she mentioned considering a change of environment but is worried about the current unfavorable situation. We should find some time to properly talk her through it.
Li Meiling: Alright, when she returns to Fujian next time, the three of us should get together properly.
Chef Chen: Xiao Song, have you been experimenting with any new desserts lately?
Song Yajing: Hello, Teacher Chen! I've recently become fascinated with researching tiramisu. I've already mastered the basics, but I always feel like there isn't enough variety.
Chef Chen: Tiramisu is indeed a classic and highly adaptable. In which direction are you thinking of taking it?

Song Yajing: I want to learn how to create different flavors, such as pairing with various types of alcohol (rum, coffee liqueur) or fruits (strawberries, mangoes), and even changing the base of the ladyfingers. It feels like there's so much depth to this, and it's what I'm most eager to master right now.
Master Chen: That's a great idea. There are indeed many variations you can explore with tiramisu. I'll focus on this part for the next advanced class in the studio and notify you when it's scheduled.
Li Meiling: Jingjing, are you busy? I just had a phone call with Jiajia.
Song Yajing: Just finished tidying up the shop, getting ready to go home. What's wrong with Jiajia? From your tone, it seems like she's not very happy?

Li Meiling: Yeah, she's been really stressed out at work lately. She said she's been dealing with a big client from Hebei who's in the e-commerce system business. The client changes their mind three times a day, and communication is a real headache—heavy accent, and they're never on the same page.
Song Yajing: Sigh, being an internet product manager means encountering all sorts of bizarre clients. Even someone as capable as Jiajia finds it a headache, so is the project likely to be delayed?

Li Meiling: Absolutely. She said the progress has slowed down a lot, and she has to work overtime every day dealing with this client, which has even raised her blood pressure. Thankfully, as teachers and shop owners, we don’t have to face such situations. How has your business been lately?
Mrs. Liu: Yajing, I've been thinking about replacing our old oven at home recently. Which model have you taken a liking to? Share your thoughts with me.
Song Yajing: Lily, I've researched for a long time! In the end, I think for us amateur enthusiasts with some aspirations, the features don't need to be fancy, but the basics must be solid.

Song Yajing: I value three points the most: first, the temperature must be accurate, and it's best to have independent temperature control for the upper and lower heating elements; otherwise, baking cakes and cookies can easily fail. Second, the hot air circulation must be even, so that cookies or multi-layered macarons will have consistent coloring.
Mrs. Liu: That makes sense! Inaccurate temperature readings are truly a nightmare. And what about the third point?

Song Yajing: The third point is that the inner pot should be easy to clean! Enamel or porcelain-coated ones are great—after baking, grease stains wipe right off, making things much more convenient. I think those smart internet-connected features are more flashy than practical. It would be better to use that part of the cost on better heating elements and temperature controllers.
Li Meiling: Jingjing, have you heard what Jiajia said? She's been so overwhelmed by house hunting lately.
Song Yajing: Not yet. The store has been busy lately, so I haven't had the chance to talk in detail. Which property has she taken a liking to now?

Li Meiling: It's still in the Nanshan Technology Park area, they say it's for the children's future schooling. They've taken a liking to one apartment, but the total price is around 12 million yuan, and the down payment pressure is just too high.
Song Yajing: Oh my, the housing prices in Shenzhen are truly out of reach. The pressure here in Xiamen is also quite high, but it’s still far from Shenzhen. What does Jiajia plan to do?

Li Meiling: She said she's trying to figure out how to gather the money, possibly by selling some of the Tencent and Alibaba stocks she bought earlier. Sigh, for folks like us living in a small city, just hearing about it feels stressful. Thankfully, it doesn't directly concern us.
Chef Chen: Xiao Song, have you been trying any new recipes lately? I saw the cake decorating in your WeChat Moments, and you've made great progress.

Song Yajing: Hello, Teacher Chen! Thank you for the compliment. I've been practicing cream smoothing and piping repeatedly lately, and I feel much better at controlling the consistency of the cream than before.
Master Chen: Good. Which cream do you usually use now? Everyone has different habits, and the most important thing is to find what works best for you.

Song Yajing: I've tried several brands, and currently, the one I find most convenient and love the most is Blue Windmill. I think its milky aroma is just right—not too overpowering. Plus, I’ve discovered a little secret: adding a tiny bit of sea salt while whipping it can really elevate the sweetness, bringing out a whole new level of depth.

Chef Chen: Blue Windmill is indeed good, with great stability. Adding sea salt is a smart idea—it helps cut through the richness and enhance the flavor. It seems you've developed your own preferences. Keep up the good work!
Li Meiling: Jingjing, have you been in touch with Jiajia recently? She seems to have some worries.
Song Yajing: We had a video chat last week, and she's been quite busy with work. What's bothering her?
Li Meiling: Her mother arranged a match for her, a doctor working at a hospital in Shenzhen, with quite good conditions.

Li Meiling: But Jiajia said after meeting twice, she felt the other person was nice, just too dull to chat with, always talking about medical topics. She's now struggling with whether to continue seeing him.
Song Yajing: Haha, Jiajia's personality really requires someone she can chat with. I'll ask her about it later.
Mrs. Liu: Yajing, have you made any new desserts recently? I tried matcha raw chocolate and sent you a picture.

Song Yajing: Wow, that looks great! I've been experimenting with peanut brittle lately. Since my parents moved in with us, they've developed a taste for it, but they need to watch their sugar intake as they're getting older.
Mrs. Liu: Traditional peanut brittle is typically heavy on oil and sugar. Have you altered the recipe?

Song Yajing: Yes, I tried several times. I replaced part of the white sugar with trehalose, reduced the amount of maltose, and added some chia seeds to enhance the texture. My dad said the sweetness was just right, and the crispiness wasn't too far off.
Mrs. Liu: Filial piety! That's a great idea—it preserves the traditional flavor while being healthier. Could you share the recipe?
Li Meiling: Jingjing, have you been in touch with Jiajia lately? It seems like she's not quite herself.
Song Yajing: We had a video call last night. She said the project pressure in Shenzhen has been particularly intense lately, with overtime work every day, and she feels extremely tense.
Li Meiling: No wonder. Did she mention specifically what's bothering her?

Song Yajing: She said the hardest part is not being able to sleep at night, with her mind full of work-related thoughts. She lies in bed for two or three hours without falling asleep, and the next day she feels even more exhausted. I feel tired just listening to her.

Li Meiling: Sigh, that's just how the internet industry is. We're too far away to be of much help, so all we can do is comfort her more. You've been busy at the shop lately, so make sure to take care of yourself and get some rest.

Song Yajing: Yes, my work here is just routine tasks like purchasing and organizing goods, which can't compare to the mental pressure she faces. I suggested she come back to Xiamen to relax whenever she has time, so the three of us can have a good get-together.
Mrs. Liu: Yajing, have you tried any new flavors of cake recently? I made a matcha red bean one, and it turned out pretty good.
Song Yajing: Matcha red bean is a classic flavor. I've recently become obsessed with experimenting with cream frosting and have tried several different combinations.
Mrs. Liu: Quick, tell me, what new discoveries have you made? I'm worried about what flavor to make next time.

Song Yajing: My favorite is to grind Earl Grey tea leaves and mix them into the cream, then add a squeeze of lemon juice and some lemon zest. The tea aroma is quite unique, with a hint of bergamot, complemented by the freshness of lemon, making it not greasy at all. It pairs perfectly with sponge cake or pound cake.
Mrs. Liu: That sounds very sophisticated! Earl Grey tea and lemon are indeed a perfect match. It's much more layered than plain vanilla or chocolate cream. I'll give it a try next time!
Mrs. Liu: Yajing, I recently made a matcha mille crepe, and I feel the quality of the matcha powder really makes a huge difference to the final product. Which brand do you use?
Song Yajing: I'm using the "Wakadake" one, the color and fragrance are both nice. How have you been lately? Still busy with illustration?

Mrs. Liu: I've taken on a small illustration project, but there's no rush. The main thing is that my husband's company is wrapping up a project recently, and he's been so busy he can barely catch his breath.
Song Yajing: Ah, you've worked hard. Is it the car-related project you mentioned before?

Mrs. Liu: Yes, that's the one. His team developed a core algorithm for the battery management system of new energy vehicles, which reportedly significantly improved performance. The company even specially commended their team a few days ago and awarded them a bonus. He can finally breathe a little easier now.

Chen Zhiqiang: Honey, the kindergarten teacher posted the registration form for summer interest classes in the group chat, and I see many parents discussing it. What do you think we should enroll Xuanxuan in? Piano or dance?
Song Yajing: I've seen them. Both piano and ballet are good, but I think they might be a bit too restrictive for Xuanxuan at her age. Doesn't she always like to doodle on the walls at home?
Chen Zhiqiang: You mean learning to paint? There are also calligraphy classes, which can help calm the mind.

Song Yajing: Calligraphy demands high standards for posture and pen-holding, and I'm afraid she might lack the patience. I think a children's painting class is excellent—it doesn't restrict imagination and allows self-expression through colors and shapes, offering so much freedom. Moreover, it will help develop an aesthetic sense in the future, which is somewhat related to my line of work.
Chen Zhiqiang: That makes sense. How about we sign up for a painting class first? Let's go check out the environment of the "Rainbow Children's Art" classroom this weekend.

Mingyuan: Yajing, I heard you sprained your ankle. Are you feeling better now? It's only been a little over a week since you started your morning runs, and you're already injured. You really need to rest well. If you need any help with the shop or the kids, just let me know.
summarized_info: Received a text message from Wang Mingyuan, which included greetings regarding the sprained foot and mentioned, 'I started sticking to morning runs just over a week ago and already got injured.'

message_content: Jiajia: Jingjing, I saw the annual plan you posted, and your goals are so clear! Regarding the part about enhancing online interaction, I have a friend who did exceptionally well after taking an online fashion course. If you're interested, I can share their information with you for reference.
Hello Miss Song, I have received the items you purchased on my behalf. The packaging is exceptionally exquisite, and the products fully match the description. Thank you so much!
Song Yajing: Xiaomei, the Spring Festival holiday schedule is set. The shop will be closed starting from New Year's Eve on January 28th. Please remember to arrange your travel plans home in advance.
summarized_info: I sent a text message to inform the clerk Xiaomei that the shop will be closed for the Spring Festival holiday starting from New Year's Eve (January 28th).

message_content: Meiling, I'm sorry, but I won't be able to make it to today's gathering. Something urgent came up that I need to attend to.
Meiling, are you free tomorrow afternoon? I've been feeling really down lately and would like to have a good talk with you.
I'm free! What's wrong? I'm really worried about you. Let's meet tomorrow at 2:30 PM at our usual spot, Le Cui Cafe, and have a good chat.

Sister Yajing, I followed your suggestion and used the color layering method this morning, and the result for the early spring commuting area turned out exceptionally well! The method you taught in the 'Spring Theme Display' module during last night's online class was truly practical.

Hello Mr. Wang! This is Song Yajing, whom you met at the community event last night. Thank you for adding me! I’d like to invite you to visit my store when you have time, so we can discuss potential collaborations, such as working together on some promotional activities.

【Ping An Insurance】Ms. Song Yajing, your family insurance application materials have been submitted, and the initial premium has been paid. The policy will take effect on August 15, 2025. If you have any questions, please contact customer service.
Customer (Ms. Lin): Boss Song, the logistics for the scarf I ordered on your mini-program hasn't been updated for several days. Could you help follow up on it?

Dear Mr. Chen,  

I am Song Yajing, a clothing store owner from Guangzhou. I learned about you through our supplier Susan and truly admire your resources and insight. I would love to explore potential collaboration opportunities with you. Would it be convenient to have a phone call tomorrow to discuss further?  

I have already added you on WeChat. Please accept my request when it’s convenient for you.
Mom, I just came back from a walk with Dad. He was in a really good mood today, talking a lot on his own and saying that the environment here in Xiamen is really nice.

Meiling, thank you so much for yesterday afternoon. After talking with you, I felt much more relaxed and clearer in my mind. Your words gave me great encouragement and support. I will gradually adjust myself—let’s keep going together!
Mrs. Liu, I've just completed the online registration for the advanced French pastry course. I'm so excited!
What I want to learn most is how to make macarons, and I hope to master the essence this time!

Received! The funds will be proportionally allocated from our store's online profits, which makes it clearer. As for management, we'll follow last night's discussion and deposit them into that low-risk XX Bank Monthly Profit product, with the goal of taking the baby on a trip to Europe or Japan within three years. We'll review the progress during the quarterly check-ins.

Me: Meiling, the low-sugar fruit tea cake I attempted to make yesterday was a complete failure. The cake collapsed badly, and the texture was very dense, not fluffy at all. The most frustrating part was that the sweetness was too low, and the flavor of the fruit tea didn’t come through, making the whole thing feel quite off.

Mom: Jingjing, have you finished practicing the piano during the lunch break? How are you doing with "Twinkle, Twinkle, Little Star" and the new song "Ode to Joy" that the teacher taught?

Me: Just finished. I’ve practiced both songs thoroughly and can play them relatively smoothly now.

Mom, the results of today's gynecological exam came back, and everything is normal, so you can rest assured. This incident also served as a wake-up call for me—health management and career advancement should go hand in hand. I plan to sign up for the online course "A Brief History of Western Clothing Development" this afternoon, so I can seize the moment and improve my professional skills.

Honey, I'm sorry, but I have to work overtime tonight to handle the store's accounts. Let's reschedule the family activity we planned for another day. I just finished my tax class and feel that some things need to be dealt with urgently.

Daughter: Mom, where should I throw the eggshells and milk cartons from breakfast?  
Me: Eggshells are kitchen waste, so put them in the green bin. Milk cartons are recyclables, so put them in the blue bin. Starting today, you'll be the family's little waste-sorting captain, responsible for supervising!

Yajing: Meiling, thank you for your recommendation! Speaking of health, it suddenly occurred to me that our family's protection also needs attention. It's time to review our family insurance policies.

Zhiqiang: Just now, I saw you play the beginning parts of "Twinkle, Twinkle, Little Star" and "Ode to Joy" from memory. Although it was a bit rusty, the melodies were all correct. These two months of learning haven’t been in vain!
summarized_info: Song Yajing received a text message from her husband, mentioning that she played the first half of "Twinkle, Twinkle, Little Star" and "Ode to Joy" from memory.

message_content: Li Hua: Jingjing, I heard you sprained your left ankle while moving goods in the store. Are you feeling better now? Make sure to take good care of yourself during the recovery period.
Aunt Zhang: Yajing, the fruit tea at today's community event was especially popular, and all the neighbors praised it for being delicious!
Yajing, regarding the matter of setting up a clothing display corner in the cafe, let's discuss the specific implementation and discount plan in detail on Saturday afternoon.
Ling, today's deep conversation really helped me release a lot of emotions. I sincerely appreciate your encouragement and support. I feel much better now and want to actively adjust my mindset.
Xiaomei, I ordered a grilled chicken breast salad with vinaigrette dressing and just warm water. I've started sticking to a healthy diet.

Zhiqiang, yesterday's professional skin test results pointed out my dryness issue. But this morning, after using the newly purchased skincare products, my skin immediately felt moisturized. I will continue to stick to my skincare routine tonight.
Yuexuan: Mom, I have some newly bought cookies here. Would you like to have one?

Me: Sweetie, Mommy can't have cookies right now. The doctor said I need to control my sugar intake. I only had unsweetened lemon water after dinner today. How about we make some healthy snacks together this weekend?

Jingjing, yesterday we talked about your discomfort in the shoulders and neck, so make sure to get plenty of rest. Health issues should never be overlooked, and it's also important to regularly review the protection for the whole family.

Xiaomei, let me emphasize the key service points during the event: smile service, fast checkout, and zero errors in shipping. The transportation arrangements have been confirmed. Please refer to the notice I will organize later for details.

Mom: Jingjing, I noticed you were walking slowly during your morning exercise. Is your ankle still bothering you? After you sprained it while moving goods at the store last time, the doctor said you should take it step by step and not rush to regain your strength.

Yajing, this is Susan. Among the spring new arrivals, there is a dress called 'Code X' with a very strong design sense. The fabric is made of imported Tencel cotton, and I have a feeling it will be very popular in your Zhongshan Road area. I highly recommend you order some.

Sister Jing, it's Vivian here. Have you gotten any new stock recently? I saw a friend on my social media trying on a dress called 'Starry Sea' at a shop on Zhongshan Road. It looked absolutely stunning and seemed like it could be from your store.

You found out, Vivian! Yes, it's exactly the design we discussed last time. The supplier named its series 'Starry Sea,' and it has only been on the shelves for a week, with fantastic feedback. Would you like to give it a try? I've saved the right size for you.

Hello Xiao Song, this is Master Chen. The studio has recently launched a new weekend advanced class, which focuses on teaching more complex French pastry techniques, such as puff pastry desserts. It’s particularly suitable for students like you who have a foundation and are looking to improve. If you’re interested, feel free to learn more about it.

Lingling, I've decided to sign up for Teacher Chen's "French Mille-Feuille and Puff Pastry Specialized Class"! Although it's a bit challenging, just thinking about being able to make even more beautiful desserts gets me excited.

Honey, my project here is almost finished, and I'll be back in Xiamen tomorrow. I saw the fruit tea bags from that popular brand you mentioned, and I bought some since the price was reasonable. I'll bring them back for you to try.

Mom, Ah Qiang is back, and he brought the brand of fruit tea you mentioned wanting to try in our last video call. He said he bought it during his layover at Guangzhou Airport. The packaging looks really nice, and we'll brew some for you to taste tonight.

Yajing, I went to SM Plaza today and had quite a fruitful trip! I bought a coat with amazing texture and also picked up a dress similar to the one you recommended before. The coat was over two thousand yuan after the discount, which made my wallet ache a bit, but I really love it.

By the way, I wore that camel coat I shared in the group chat to school today, and several colleagues asked for the link! Your taste is truly sharp—it pairs perfectly with that floral dress from your shop.

Dear Sister Yajing, peace be with you in the Lord. Recently, there have been more activities in the parish. Thanks be to God, two new believers are willing to join the service of the catechumen class and the scripture reading group. May the Lord bless their devotion.

Yajing, regarding the dedicated volunteers we mentioned last time, we now have three new friends who are consistently participating in the service, and they have been a great help, especially in caring for the elderly in the community. The work of the Lord truly requires more people to join hands.

Xiao Jing, didn't you plan an overseas trip? I think both Japan and Thailand are great options for a family's first trip abroad. Japan offers excellent shopping and family-friendly facilities, while Thailand is more cost-effective and has a wide variety of delicious food. You might want to look into both.

Wen, Ah Qiang and I have discussed it, and we're leaning towards going to Thailand first. It feels like there's less pressure for our first trip abroad with Xuanxuan, and the family-friendly hotel in Thailand you recommended last time has amazing reviews.

Meiling, I saw a shop exploration video today. There's a new French dessert shop opened in Xiagang, and both the decor and the desserts look amazing! Next time you and Jiajia come to Xiamen, let's go check it out together!
Haha, sure! Where exactly is it? What's the name? I'll make a note of it.
It's called 'Sweet Dreams Paris', located on Minzu Road, not far from my shop. I heard their specialties are Napoleon and raspberry tarts.

Teacher Chen, I went to your studio last week and tried the caramel sea salt fig tart—it tasted amazing! I tried making it myself later, but the crust never turned out crispy enough. Could you share some tips?

The butter used in that new product requires low-temperature handling, and also, remember to place a weight on top during baking. When are you free? You can come over again, and I'll demonstrate it for you in person.
Susan, the blue floral silk dress in the store is almost out of stock. Could you please urgently restock sizes M and L? A customer has placed an order.
Okay Yajing, I'll check the inventory. There should still be some available. I'll ship it today, and it should arrive at your store by the day after tomorrow (May 9th) at the latest.
Xiaomei, the replenishment shipment for Guangzhou, especially the blue floral dress, will be delivered this afternoon. Please make sure to sign for it and update the inventory accordingly.
Lily, take a look at this video link [link]. It's a tutorial on making macarons, and it says that using a silicone macaron mat can significantly increase the success rate. I'm planning to buy one!
Wow, I see! I bought one before, and it's indeed better than parchment paper—it doesn't slide around easily. When you buy it, make sure the size matches your baking tray.
Yajing, I want to recommend two songs that I've been playing on repeat lately! Billie Eilish's new single "Lunch" and Hozier's "Too Sweet"—both are absolutely amazing!
Haha, received! I'll also share Taylor Swift's "Fortnight" with you. The music video is really well-made.
By the way, the songs I recommended last time were great, right? I’ll add two more hidden gems: Sabrina Carpenter’s "Espresso" and Dua Lipa’s "Illusion"—they’re perfect for driving!

Yajing, we've recently launched several shirts and skirts made from triacetate satin. They have excellent drape and a sophisticated sheen, perfect for the transition from summer to autumn. Would you like to take a look?
That sounds great from the description, Susan. Do you have any pictures or color swatches? Please send them to me. Customers really like fabrics with good drape.
Mom, I took Xuanxuan to the church today for activity rehearsals. The little one was so excited and kept practicing non-stop.

Yajing, do you remember last month when you mentioned that Xuanxuan was rehearsing? For this year's Christmas Eve Mass, we would like her to perform the part of the little angel announcing the good news. What do you think?
Susan, the new batch of silk shirts your company recently launched looks good in terms of the cut. Are they from the cooperative factory in Zhejiang that was mentioned before?

Yajing, you're really something, so well-informed? That Shaoxing factory just adjusted its management, and both efficiency and quality have improved significantly, so this batch of goods has a great reputation.
Dad, how have you been lately? The Mid-Autumn Festival is approaching, and I've already booked the train tickets. Xuanxuan says she misses her grandpa.
We're all doing well. Today, I also went with your mom to that old antique shop on West Street and found a little trinket that's quite interesting. I'll show it to you when I get back.
Mom, I showed the tea tray Dad bought at the antique shop the other day to Master Chen, and he said the carving is quite unique, with a style typical of the late Qing and early Republic periods.
Sis, I read in the financial news that the market has been quite volatile this year. How is that investment you mentioned before doing?
Don't worry, we were lucky to have chosen the right track. Let's discuss it in detail next time we meet. Currently, the field of new energy battery recycling holds immense potential.
Lily, you mentioned last time that Hangzhou has introduced two new desserts featuring local ingredients. What exactly are they? Just hearing you say they're delicious has made me really crave them.

Yajing, the desserts have been sent out! Osmanthus cake and Longjing tea pastry, both are improved traditional flavors, give them a try. Let me know your feedback on my tiramisu cake once you receive it!
Ah Qiang, your car's annual inspection is coming up soon, right? Last time you mentioned wanting to upgrade something while you're at it, didn't you?

Yes, I'll install it right after the annual inspection. Haven't the news reports been frequently covering incidents of insurance fraud lately? It's more reassuring to get a dash cam with high resolution. A colleague recommended a new model from DDPAI.
Xiaomei, I need to take half a day off in late July because Xuanxuan's kindergarten is holding a singing competition, and I want to go cheer for her. I'll let you know the specific date later.
By the way, Xuanxuan's singing competition time has been confirmed. It's next Monday, July 21st, in the afternoon. I'll have to rely on you to take care of the shop that day!

Teacher Chen, I attempted to make the Napoleon mille-feuille you taught last week. The puff pastry turned out fairly successful, but the cream started to melt a bit during assembly. I'll need to ask for your guidance again in the next class.

Lily, I've been trying my hand at making crème brûlée lately, but I find it really tricky to get the heat just right. It always ends up either too soft or with an eggy smell. Could you go into more detail about the vanilla bean tip you mentioned last time?

Vivian, I have an idea to discuss with you. Since you're really good at using Xiaohongshu, I'd like to invite you to come to the store as a regular customer and take a set of photos and write a post about a 'hidden gem' shop, sharing your outfits. Of course, I'll give you the best friend discount on those new items you've had your eye on! How about we support each other?

Meiling, I'm thinking of organizing a 'Loyal Friends Appreciation Day' at the store, specifically inviting loyal customers and friends like you to enjoy an exclusive discount. How about choosing a weekend in August? It would also be a great chance for everyone to get together.

Lingling, it's been a long time since we last met! Are you free next Saturday afternoon? Xuanxuan’s dad is taking her to the science museum, so the two of us can go to that newly opened café and catch up. I’ll treat you to your favorite pour-over coffee.

Jiajia! I heard you're coming back to Xiamen in mid-August! That's fantastic! You must save a day for us—Lingling and I are really looking forward to it. How about meeting at our usual spot on Zhongshan Road?

Father Wang, hello, I'm Yajing. I would like to make an appointment in advance. This year, for Aqiang's and my wedding anniversary, we would like to hold a small family thanksgiving service at the church with Xuanxuan to thank the Lord for His blessings. When would be a convenient time for you?

Mom, I've made an appointment with Father Wang to go to the church on the weekend of our wedding anniversary in October. Will you and Dad be free to come to Xiamen then? It would be perfect for the whole family to be together.

Susan, Happy New Year! It's about time for the spring collection to launch. What are the popular trends or must-have dresses for this spring season at your end? Could you send me some pictures and price quotes?

Susan, time really flies, and it's time to think about autumn and winter collections again. This year, I want to add some high-quality coats and creatively designed knitwear to the store, at a medium price range. If you have any good suppliers, please remember to recommend them to me. I might come to check out the goods in October.

(Community Mom Group) 'Today's upcycling event was fantastic - learned new skills while being eco-friendly! When can we have another one?' 'Same here! I hope we can have activities like this regularly, and it's great to bring the kids along too!' 'Please notify us in advance for the next event - I'll bring more old clothes!'

Susan: Yajing, thank you for the invitation. I will definitely visit you in Xiamen when I have the chance. As for the fabric we just discussed, I have arranged for expedited sampling, and the initial samples are expected to be ready next week.
Zhiqiang: I'm heading out to take care of those matters.
Mom: Jingjing, I've sent you the recipe for tiramisu on WeChat, remember to check it. Come home for dinner when you have time.
I've completed the personal income tax declaration, handled it at home, and it went quite smoothly.

Me: Mom, I just got back from Guangzhou and will be home today. The signal was poor on the train, and I just got out of the station. Luckily, I bought some things in advance, and I need to quickly check the windows and other things at home.
Mrs. Liu: Yajing, this fruit tea has a particularly strong aroma when brewed. I'm giving it to you to try, and I hope you like it.

Song Yajing: Susan, I've noted down the details of the F/W series we discussed on the phone. Once you send over the design drafts and fabric swatch photos, I'll carefully review them in light of our budget, particularly focusing on the knitwear styles and trouser cuts.
Honey, don't forget we have a formal financial meeting at home at nine tonight. Let's go over yesterday's plan in detail again.

Auntie Lin, this is Song Yajing. While volunteering at the church yesterday, I experienced a sense of inner peace and fulfillment, which has led me to decide to participate regularly in the monthly volunteer service from now on. How should I arrange this?

Mrs. Liu, I've received the tea bags. Thank you so much! While brainstorming ideas for a new cake last night, the peach oolong tea bags you sent gave me fantastic inspiration. I tried making it today, and I'm sure they were a great help.

Sister Li: Okay, Jingjing, let's tentatively schedule to sign the lease renewal contract next Tuesday at noon at Le Cui Cafe. Please send me a WeChat message the day before to confirm the specific time.
Susan: Ms. Song, we have discussed and basically confirmed the core three styles and preliminary quantities for the autumn order, with details to be refined later.
Mom, we've just set off for Quanzhou, the National Day holiday has begun!
Yajing, remember the English enlightenment method I mentioned last time? Using English stories to immerse Lexuan in the language works really well; you should give it a try.
Zhiqiang, the lunch was delicious! The time spent at the church this morning gave me a lot of thoughts, and it was really nice to chat with you all during lunch.
Yajing, how's the preparation going for the 'secret weapon' you're bringing to tomorrow's gathering? We're all eagerly waiting!

Zhiqiang: I'm almost done with the financial evaluation report. By the way, regarding whether to rent a place or live together, the more I think about it, the more I feel it's better to live separately. Our lifestyle habits are different from our parents', including daily routines and dietary preferences. Living under the same roof for a long time would inevitably lead to friction. Renting a place in the same neighborhood would allow us to take care of them while maintaining our independence.

Susan: Yajing, I have reviewed the electronic version of the contract and the sample images, and everything looks good. The price will be as per our final confirmation. Wishing you a smooth and successful Mid-Autumn Festival collaboration and promotion!

Mom: Ordering takeout today, the waste sorting for meal boxes is so complicated. The plastic cups should be washed and placed in the recyclable bin, but I'm not sure where to put the greasy packaging paper.

Me: Mom, the third lesson this Saturday is finally over. The teacher said I played "Twinkle, Twinkle, Little Star" much more smoothly! Although my wrist is still a bit tired, I'm so happy to be praised.
Jingjing, remember to come to the church for choir rehearsal tomorrow, I'll introduce you.
